{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650928"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18425"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18425"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114242"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11143"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96242"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"},{"type":"tags","id":"10264"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114242"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscles can contract in different ways depending on the relationship between the force generated and the resistance encountered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about isotonic muscle contractions is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Isotonic concentric contractions involve muscle shortening","Isotonic eccentric contractions occur without tension development","Isotonic eccentric contractions involve muscle shortening","Isotonic contractions occur without any change in muscle length","Isotonic concentric contractions involve muscle lengthening"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring \u003Cstrong\u003Eisotonic concentric contractions\u003C/strong\u003E, the muscle generates force that exceeds the opposing load, resulting in\u003Cstrong\u003E muscle shortening. \u003C/strong\u003EA common example is the biceps muscle contracting to lift a dumbbell during an arm curl.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic eccentric contractions occur without tension development\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as eccentric contractions do develop tension as the muscle lengthens in a controlled manner. \u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic eccentric contractions involve muscle shortening\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because eccentric contractions involve controlled lengthening of the muscle. \u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic contractions occur without any change in muscle length\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since by definition, isotonic contractions involve length changes while maintaining constant tension. \u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic concentric contractions involve muscle lengthening\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as concentric contractions involve shortening, not lengthening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn all isotonic contractions, the tension (force) remains relatively constant while the muscle length changes. This differs from isometric contractions where length stays constant but tension varies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Isotonic contractions involve a change in muscle length while maintaining constant tension.","Concentric contractions result in muscle shortening, while eccentric contractions result in muscle lengthening.","Understanding the differences between isotonic and isometric contractions is crucial for comprehending muscle physiology."],"references":["Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96242"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18425"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96242"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:06:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:06:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11143"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114242"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"